1. Multi-line question parsing is broken: questions that span multiple lines/paragraphs
   are split into separate Q&A pairs. The sample output shows "Did Bloom discover common
   factors of similarity between their respective" parsed as one question (with empty answer)
   and "like and unlike reactions to experience?" as another. This inflates the pair count
   from the expected ~309 to 390. Fix: join consecutive paragraphs that appear to be
   continuations of a question (e.g., paragraphs that don't start with a capital letter
   after an interrogative opener, or paragraphs that end with "?" but don't start with
   an interrogative word and follow a non-question paragraph).

2. The "other" question type category is too large (38.7%, 151 pairs). Many of these are
   continuation fragments from bug #1. After fixing #1, re-evaluate whether additional
   interrogative patterns are needed (e.g., questions starting with "In", "For", "To",
   "By" that are still interrogative in structure).

3. Triple extraction: apostrophe/punctuation appearing as the most common subject (42
   occurrences). Filter out non-alphabetic tokens before selecting subjects and objects
   in the POS-pattern extraction loop.

4. Triple extraction: function words ("the", "with", "and", "from", "which", "his") are
   appearing as top objects. The forward-search heuristic for object nouns is picking up
   determiners and prepositions that the POS tagger has mistagged. Add a stopword filter
   to exclude common function words from subject and object positions.

5. Triple extraction: "s" appears as the 2nd most common predicate (41 times). This is
   the possessive "'s" being split by the tokenizer. Filter out single-character predicates
   or handle possessives explicitly.

6. Triple extraction: "faded" (32 times) and "contain" (39 times) appear as top subjects,
   suggesting adjectives and verbs are being mistagged as nouns. Consider requiring that
   subject/object candidates have NN/NNP/NNS/NNPS tags specifically, rather than just
   startswith('NN').

7. Topic classifier: "other" absorbs 55.1% of Ithaca questions and 90.5% of Calypso
   sentences. The keyword lists are too narrow. Expand keyword sets, especially for
   categories like "daily_routine", "food_drink", "body/health", "history/memory",
   and "emotion/inner_life" (which the exercise specifically asks about but is missing
   from the current taxonomy).

8. Topic comparison methodology: Ithaca is classified per Q&A pair while Calypso is
   classified per sentence. These are different units of analysis -- a single Ithaca Q&A
   pair may be much longer than a Calypso sentence. Normalize by word count or use the
   same segmentation unit for both.

9. Min answer length of 0 words confirms empty answers exist from the multi-line question
   splitting bug. After fixing #1, verify that no legitimate Q&A pairs have empty answers.

10. No networkx graph visualization is produced, despite the exercise calling for one.
    The code extracts triples but never builds or visualizes a graph. Add graph construction
    and visualization (or at minimum export the triples for external visualization).

11. No treemap visualization is produced for topic distribution, despite Exercise 3
    specifically requesting one (squarify or plotly.express.treemap). Only a text-based
    bar is printed.
